<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900817-0032</DOCNO><DOCID>900817-0032.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   U.S. Arrests Boy, 5 Others   In Computer Hacker Cases   ----   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup</HL><DATE>08/17/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><LP>   New York state and federal investigators arrested a14-year-old boy who was suspected of using a home computer tobreak into a Pentagon computer used by the office of theSecretary of the Air Force.   Investigators also searched 17 locations yesterday in NewYork, Westchester County and Long Island, seizing computerequipment and data storage devices. Five men, ranging in agefrom 17 to 32, were arrested in the sweep and charged withcomputer tampering and trespass, unauthorized entry and theftof services. They were suspected of breaking into a computerat the City University of Bellevue, Wash. Investigators saidthe 14-year-old was also linked to the Bellevue intrusion.</LP><TEXT>   The arrests were part of a two-month investigation by theNew York state police, U.S. Secret Service, Air Force Officeof Special Investigations, the New York attorney general andother agencies.   Major Steve Headley of the Air Force investigations officesaid the Pentagon computer that was penetrated was part of anadministrative network and did not contain any classifiedinformation. &quot;There was no breach of national security,&quot; hesaid.   Investigators did not release the name of the 14-year-old,who will be charged as a juvenile delinquent.</TEXT></DOC>